{
  "family": "Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag Reaction (Remote Functionalization)",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "CCCCN(C)Cl"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "C1CCNC1C"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "O=S(=O)(O)O"
    ],
    "rationale": "This is a classic and simple example of the Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag reaction. The substrate, N-chloro-N-methylbutan-1-amine, undergoes intramolecular 1,5-hydrogen atom transfer from the delta-carbon to the nitrogen radical under acidic conditions (e.g., sulfuric acid), followed by cyclization to form the pyrrolidine ring. This example clearly demonstrates the key C-H activation at a remote (delta) position and subsequent C-N bond formation, which are the defining features of this reaction.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The reaction involves an acyclic amine precursor forming a heterocyclic product via a radical mechanism. It avoids complex functional groups, arenes, or other motifs that could be confused with reactions like the Barton reaction (which typically involves alcohols/nitrites) or the Hofmann rearrangement (which involves amides). The simplicity of the N-chloro-N-alkylamine substrate and the formation of a simple pyrrolidine ring makes it a distinct and canonical example."
  }
}
